  "text": "Kubernetes CNI (Container Network Interface) integration is implemented across multiple components in the kubernetes/kubernetes repository. The architecture follows a delegation model where the kubelet coordinates with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI) to handle CNI plugin invocation.\n\n## Network Plugin Manager and Pod Lifecycle Integration\n\nThe network plugin manager functionality is distributed across several key components:\n\n1. **Kubelet Network Management** (pkg/kubelet/kubelet_network.go, kubelet_network_linux.go): The Kubelet maintains pod CIDR configuration and triggers network plugin updates through the updatePodCIDR() function. This is where the kubelet coordinates with network providers and ensures pods are assigned IP addresses from the node's allocated CIDR range.\n\n2. **Pod Sandbox Creation and Network Namespace Setup** (pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/kuberuntime_sandbox.go, kuberuntime_sandbox_linux.go): When syncing a pod, the kubelet's kubeGenericRuntimeManager calls createPodSandbox() which delegates to generatePodSandboxConfig(). This function generates the PodSandboxConfig that includes network configuration:\n   - generatePodSandboxLinuxConfig() sets up Linux-specific network namespace modes through NamespacesForPod()\n   - Namespace mode (HOST or POD) is determined via NetworkNamespaceForPod() in pkg/kubelet/kuberuntime/util/util.go\n   - The configuration is passed to the CRI runtime via RunPodSandbox()\n\n3. **CNI Plugin Invocation** (staging/src/k8s.io/cri-api and staging/src/k8s.io/cri-client): The actual CNI plugin invocation happens in the CRI layer:\n   - PodSandboxConfig (defined in api.pb.go) contains NetworkConfig with pod networking parameters\n   - The instrumented_services.go wraps RuntimeService calls including RunPodSandbox()\n   - remote_runtime.go in cri-client connects to the CRI runtime server (e.g., containerd)\n   - The CRI runtime is responsible for calling CNI plugins based on the network configuration\n\n## IP Address Management (IPAM)\n\nThe IPAM implementation is split between node-level and service-level IP allocation:\n\n1. **Node IPAM Controller** (pkg/controller/nodeipam/): Allocates CIDR blocks to nodes:\n   - NewNodeIpamController() initializes the IPAM controller\n   - The controller uses rangeAllocator (in ipam/range_allocator.go) to allocate CIDR ranges from the cluster's pod CIDR\n   - cidrset/cidr_set.go manages the CIDR blocks and available IP ranges\n   - Each node receives a /24 (or configurable) subnet for pod IPs\n   - updatePodCIDR() in kubelet_network.go receives these allocations and configures the network on the node\n\n2. **Service IP Allocation** (pkg/registry/core/service/ipallocator/): Allocates IPs for Kubernetes Services:\n   - IPAllocator and CIDRAllocator interfaces define IP allocation contracts\n   - bitmap.go uses bitmap-based allocation for efficient IP management\n   - The repair controller (controller/repair.go, repairip.go) maintains consistency of allocated IPs\n\n## Network Configuration Flow During Pod Creation\n\nThe complete network setup flow during pod creation:\n\n1. kubelet.syncPod() initiates pod synchronization\n2. kubeGenericRuntimeManager.SyncPod() orchestrates the sync process\n3. createPodSandbox() is called to set up pod-level networking\n4. generatePodSandboxConfig() builds the network configuration including:\n   - Port mappings (kubecontainer.MakePortMappings())\n   - DNS configuration (GetPodDNS() from kubelet_network.go)\n   - Linux namespace modes (NamespacesForPod() for network, IPC, PID namespaces)\n5. generatePodSandboxLinuxConfig() sets security context with NamespaceOption\n6. The config is passed to CRI.RunPodSandbox() via instrumented_services.go\n7. The CRI runtime (containerd/cri-o) receives RunPodSandboxRequest with network config\n8. The CRI runtime invokes CNI plugins (add command) to:\n   - Set up network namespace\n   - Allocate IP from pod CIDR (via CNI IPAM plugin)\n   - Configure network interfaces\n   - Set up default routes\n9. Pod's sandbox is created with network namespace\n10. Containers are created in the pod's network namespace\n11. kuberuntime_sandbox.go's determinePodSandboxIPs() retrieves the assigned IP from the runtime\n12. Status is updated with pod IP for service discovery\n\n## Key Files for CNI Integration\n\n- **kuberuntime_sandbox.go**: Entry point for pod network setup via CRI\n- **kubelet_network.go**: Coordinates with network providers and IPAM\n- **node_ipam_controller.go**: Allocates pod CIDR ranges to nodes\n- **api.pb.go**: Defines CRI PodSandboxConfig network structure\n- **remote_runtime.go**: CRI client connecting to runtime for CNI delegation\n- **util.go**: Namespace configuration utilities for container network modes\n\nThe design maintains separation of concerns: Kubernetes manages IP address allocation and network configuration metadata, while the CRI runtime delegates actual CNI plugin invocation to plugins like Calico, Flannel, Weave, and others."
